<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0843-B"><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>In Singapore, a line at a bookstore on the Orchard Road shopping belt grew throughout the morning, but dwindled to just a handful of eager readers an hour before the sale began.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050717.0460"><line>Scholastic had printed an unprecedented 10.8 million copies the first time around, but pre-release sales were so brisk it rushed a second printing, the company said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>&quot;I don't like that.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>A global phenomenon, the Harry Potter books have been translated into 62 languages and have inspired a series of films.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="43"><scu uid="34" label="The Potter books have been translated into 63 languages" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>For the first time, Scholastic provided the National Braille Press with an advance copy of the Harry Potter book, which is kept under tight wraps.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0346"><line>It's the sixth in J.K. Rowling's seven-book fantasy series on the young wizard.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050715.0335"><line>Adding to the sense of magic, a giant image of the front cover of the latest book -- which shows Potter and his headmaster Professor Albus Dumbledore, with wands poised, surrounded by fire -- will be beamed overhead.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>The fantasy series is hugely popular in China.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050715.0335"><line>Accompanied by their parents or guardians, the fans will be driven in horse-drawn carriages to the castle, where fire-eaters, jugglers and torch throwers are due to be performing outside.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051001.0176"><line>Outlets in Switzerland preferred to wait until dawn on Saturday to open their doors, but still saw a &quot;blistering start&quot; to sales at FNAC stores with less of a rush at competitors Payot.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051015.0135"><line>Many of the children who attended the event, which featured a light-show and other special effects, dressed as their favourite character from J.K. Rowling's series of books about a boy wizard at a boarding school.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>A blind reader's options are relatively limited, however.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050717.0460"><line>&quot;Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince&quot; shattered publishing records in the United States, selling 6.9 million copies in its first 24 hours on sale, its US publisher Scholastic said Sunday.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="8" sums="11,12,29,37,38,41,49,55"><scu uid="23" label="In the first 24 hours, the book sold 6.9 million copies in the US" weight="3"/><scu uid="40" label="The book shattered records in the United States" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>On the Net:</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051015.0135"><line>State-owned post office CTT said it would deliver 3,500 copies of the book to homes across the country between Saturday and Monday.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050715.0335"><line>At one minute past midnight on Saturday morning (2301 GMT Friday), she will read them the first chapter of the sixth and penultimate volume of her world famous series about the magical adventures of Potter and his friends.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>Thousands of Harry Potter fans across Asia donned black cloaks, witches' caps and wire-rimmed glasses to cheer the arrival of the latest installment in the boy-wizard's adventures.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="29,55"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051015.0137"><line>Since first Harry Potter debut in China in 2000, the previous five book series have sold more than 7.14 million copies so far in the mainland, with the average record hitting 1.43 million.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>&quot;A lot of books aren't available in Braille,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051015.0137"><line>In order to beat pirates, the publishing house used a special kind of green paper as its cover and employed the state of the art technology.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050717.0460"><line>A second printing of the sixth volume in J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series is already hitting US bookstores, the firm said.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="37,6"><scu uid="26" label="The second printing hit bookstores immediately." weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051001.0176"><line>Publishers Gallimard have printed a record two million French copies of the penultimate tome in British author J.K. Rowling's astronomically successful series, predicting a fresh outbreak of the &quot;Pottermania&quot; which has surrounded previous installments of the boy wizard's adventures.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="16,3,35"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050712.0577"><line>While those, too, were shrouded in secrecy, extreme pains were taken this time around to safeguard the storyline, because the author had previously hinted that one of the main characters would die.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>A local lumber retailer donated $100,000 (euro83,292) to help make up the difference.</line><line>More than 300 people have pre-ordered the book from NBP.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0346"><line>&quot;We don't want to ruin it for other kids and take away from the experience of everyone reading it together.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>Moss, a student at the Perkins School for the Blind in Watertown, doesn't want the book read aloud to her.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050717.0460"><line>Early reports estimate that Scholastic broke all publishing records,&quot; a Scholastic statement said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>&quot;But Harry has to move on.&quot;</line><line>He and a friend spent more than 12 hours to be the first to get their copies.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051015.0135"><line>The first book in the series, &quot;Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone&quot; sold over 400,000 copies alone in Portugal.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050715.0335"><line>The young group, aged eight to 16, won competitions in their home countries to attend an exclusive party at Edinburgh Castle, Scotland, which has been transformed into Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry to celebrate the release of &quot;Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince&quot;.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="38"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>&quot;It'll be very sad when she finishes writing the books,&quot; Jang said.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="21"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>&quot;We're not here to make a profit.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051015.0135"><line>Here books have sold more than 300 million copies worldwide in over 60 languages and the first three Potter books have already been made into blockbuster movies.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0346"><line>The book, &quot;Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince,&quot; has been shrouded in secrecy and its debut has been highly orchestrated to enable everyone _ readers and reviewers, alike _ to crack it open all at once.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="38,6"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>Tanya Holton, NBP's vice president of development, said it usually takes months, if not a year or two, for published books to make it into Braille form.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="32,5"/></line><line>&quot;Braille is such an important skill,&quot; said Charlson, who is blind.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="57"><scu uid="24" label="The Braille edition was released three days after publication" weight="4"/></annotation></line><line>It comes in nine volumes, takes up 13 1/2 inches (34 centimeters) of shelf space and weighs about 11 pounds (5 kilograms).</line><line>And for once, the 16-year-old blind student won't have to wait months longer than her sighted friends to dive into &quot;Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="38"/></line><line>&quot;When I read it in Braille, it takes me a lot longer,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>Associated Press correspondents Sylvia Hui in Hong Kong, Alexa Olesen in Beijing and En-Lai Yeoh in Singapore contributed to this report.</line><line>And because you can order it beforehand with a discount, I think many Singaporeans will take advantage of that instead,&quot; said April Lee, a marketing manager and Potter fan.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="16"><scu uid="41" label="French, Portuguese and Chinese translations came out in October" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050712.0577"><line>The grocer accidentally stocked shelves last Thursday with &quot;Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince,&quot; the sixth book in J.K. Rowling's acclaimed series, allowing some unsuspecting customers to get a sneak peak at its contents before its scheduled worldwide release on July 16.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="22,38"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050715.0335"><line>Some 2,000 local school children are also expected to gather along the main road leading to the castle to await the arrival of Rowling, 39, who is expected to make a brief appearance shortly before witching hour strikes.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>Bookstores throughout Asia and Australia opened their doors early Saturday and began handing out copies of &quot;Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince,&quot; the latest volume in J.K. Rowling's wildly popular children's series, which has sold more than 270 million copies worldwide.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="7" sums="13,29,35,36,38,43,55"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>We're here to get books in the hands of children.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051015.0137"><line>&quot;We have to prepare to quickly issue the Chinese edition to thwart the pirates,&quot; said Wang Ruiqin, editor of the series of the publishing company.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>&quot;Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince&quot; is the penultimate book in Rowling's seven-book series.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="36,38,42,44,49"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050715.0335"><line>Seventy lucky children from Australia, Britain, Canada, India, Ireland, New Zealand and South Africa will mark the midnight launch of the next Harry Potter book with the boy wizard's creator J.K. Rowling.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="23,40,42"><scu uid="27" label="J.K. Rowling hosted 70 children at Edinburgh Castle for the launch." weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>Hundreds of Potter fans crammed into one of central Sydney's largest bookstores to snatch up their copies of the 607-page tome.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>Usually, I don't want it to end.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051015.0137"><line>Although the publication of the Chinese edition of &quot;Harry Potter: The Half Blood Prince&quot; came out much faster than other translated versions, it was still not soon enough -- online editions of the book appeared only a month after the English original was launched.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="0,10,20,38,8"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051001.0176"><line>The release date was also announced in newsletters handed out at school gates and printed in youth magazines.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050715.0335"><line>In addition, a 14-year-old Welsh fan, Owen Jones, is due to conduct the only one-on-one interview with the author, which will be broadcast that evening.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051004.0497"><line>Global sales of Harry Potter books have surpassed 300 million, the agent for author J.K. Rowling said Tuesday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="12,23,25,32,44,49,57"><scu uid="39" label="More than 300 million copies of the Harry Potter books have been sold" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>It sold 200 books in the first hour and had 4,000 in stock, said spokeswoman Li Minyue.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0346"><line>Muldoon's husband said the family would return the book to the publisher, though his stepson, Sylum Mastropaolo, admitted reading about two pages.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>&quot;Pre-orders of Harry Potter six have more than doubled that of the previous Harry book,&quot; said Don Grover, the chief executive of the Dymocks Group of Companies, one of Australia's largest chain of bookstores.</line><line>Jennifer Yip, 15, said she hates reading, but described herself as a &quot;super fan&quot; of Harry Potter.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="6"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>&quot;This is not about charity.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050715.0335"><line>On Sunday, Rowling, who rarely makes public appearances, will grant her only press conference about the launch to the 70 youngsters who must then write up articles for the world's media.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0346"><line>A drug store accidentally sold a copy of the latest Harry Potter book to a woman ahead of Saturday's strict release time, but the customer said she will return it.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="6" sums="14,21,37,44,49,51"><scu uid="29" label="A US drug store accidentally sold one copy of the book ahead of the release date" weight="3"/><scu uid="38" label="The US customer who accidentally bought a copy before the launch agreed to return the book" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>Pirated versions of the first five books in the series and the movie spin-offs are widely available, but so far the latest book appears to have evaded Chinese pirates.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051001.0176"><line>&quot;Lots of people will probably buy the book in both languages, as many bought it in English for the pleasure of owning it but can't actually read it,&quot; she predicted.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050712.0577"><line>&quot;The process is ongoing right now.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0346"><line>Christine Ekblom, a manager at the upstate New York pharmacy, said she believed it was the only copy sold.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051001.0176"><line>At many bookshops, sales staff in witches' hats served up devilish delicacies and magical potions as children young and old queued way past bedtime.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="48"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>When you read one sentence, you don't want to put it down.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051001.0176"><line>Twice as many copies of the latest tome have been printed compared to volume five and three times as many as volume four.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050712.0577"><line>It involved a single store location and handful of customers.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051001.0176"><line>Booksellers across French-speaking Europe saw legions of Harry Potter fans scramble to their shelves this weekend, as the sixth book in the bestselling children's series went on sale in translation at midnight on Friday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="13,14,16,3,43,44,51"><scu uid="41" label="French, Portuguese and Chinese translations came out in October" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050715.0335"><line>Following this, Rowling will give each child a signed copy of the book for them to read over the weekend before she meets them again on Sunday to answer some questions.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>The book goes on sale at midnight Friday.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050712.0577"><line>He refused to say if any of the wayward books had been returned or even if the buyers had been identified.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050715.0335"><line>The book will be the centrepiece of a special Harry Potter display in the front entrance of the Edinburgh building.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>It's about parity,&quot; Holton said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>Rowling is now the richest woman in Britain, with a fortune estimated by Forbes magazine at US$1 billion (euro830 million).</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0346"><line>&quot;They were pulled off an hour after they were put on the shelves,&quot; Ekblom said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>For the past two weeks, more than four dozen employees at the Boston printing house have been working overtime to print a batch of 800 Braille copies of the &quot;Half-Blood Prince.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="38"/></line><line>&quot;This is the only book we have blitzed like this before, because readers are clamoring for it,&quot; Holton said.</line><line>Like millions of Harry Potter fans, Katherine Moss can't wait to get her fingers on a copy of the sixth entry in J.K. Rowling's best-selling series.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="11,3,57"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0346"><line>The company said Sylum would get a copy Saturday along with a gift pack.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>&quot;I'm an obsessed fan,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>At the Perkins School, the waiting list for the new Harry Potter book already has at least two dozen names.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0346"><line>Fourteen books were accidentally sold Thursday at a grocery store in Canada, but a judge ordered the customers not to talk about the book, copy it, sell it or even read it before its official release.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050712.0577"><line>Previous instalments of the book have sold almost 300 million copies worldwide since 1997.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="13,21"><scu uid="39" label="More than 300 million copies of the Harry Potter books have been sold" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>Seventeen-year-old Mohammed Jalili-Baleh said he couldn't wait to know what adventures awaited him inside the cover of Rowling's latest book.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051004.0497"><line>Potter books have now been translated into 63 languages, most recently Farsi.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>I don't like that at all.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051001.0176"><line>Publishers Gallimard had carefully stage-managed the launch, distributing posters of the front cover to bookstores at the start of September and installing clocks counting down the final two weeks to publication.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0346"><line>Kyle Good, a Scholastic publishing spokeswoman, said the company was not aware of any other early sales in the United States.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>&quot;Nothing compares to a kid being able to read for themselves.&quot;</line><line>Each Braille book costs $62 (euro52) to produce, but the nonprofit NBP is selling them for $17.99 (euro14.98) _ the same as Amazon.com, according to Holton.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>Dymocks said it expects to sell more than 50,000 copies of the latest Potter book on Saturday alone.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="25,6"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051015.0137"><line>The government vowed on August 17 to curb pirates in book market, including Potter VI.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>About 40 Potter fans gathered outside the Wangfujing Bookstore in downtown Beijing early Saturday to buy hardcover copies in English for 178 yuan (US$21; euro18) each.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051001.0176"><line>Internet sales have also been brisk with major retailer Amazon reporting 1.5 million orders worldwide, far outstripping the month's other major French language release, Michel Houellebecq's &quot;La Possibilite d'une Ile&quot;.</line><line>Competitor Filigranes had opened at 9:00 pm (1900 GMT) for a reservation-only evening of entertainment with quizzes, costumes and nibbles, and sold 200 copies.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>A Braille edition is due out three days later _ much earlier than with previous Harry Potter books, thanks to a new arrangement between the publisher, Scholastic Inc., and the National Braille Press in Boston.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0346"><line>Mandy Muldoon said she was shopping with her 9-year-old son when she spotted a stack of the much-anticipated books on a shelf and purchased one.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050712.0577"><line>Justice Kristi Gill ordered the 14 customers not to talk about the book, copy it, sell it or read it until after midnight on this upcoming Saturday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="19"><scu uid="32" label="A court injunction was issued to prevent the accidental Canadian purchasers from reading the book prior to the launch" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051001.0176"><line>In France, the FNAC chain ordered a massive 30,000 copies while around 15 of their stores stayed open all night, decked out with broomsticks, witches' hats, spellbooks and potions.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051015.0135"><line>Portuguese publishers Editorial Presenca have printed 150,000 copies of the Portuguese-language version of J.K. Rowling's &quot;Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince&quot;, which was first published worldwide in English in July.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="9" sums="19,29,33,37,38,44,48,57,6"><scu uid="41" label="French, Portuguese and Chinese translations came out in October" weight="3"/></annotation></line><line>Several bookstores, and five post offices, in Lisbon and second-city Oporto in the north opened their doors at midnight on Friday to sell the penultimate tome in the bestselling series.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051001.0176"><line>&quot;I've done nothing but stack shelves all day,&quot; one FNAC manager in Geneva said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>She wants to savor each word of the text at her own pace.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050715.0335"><line>The multi-millionaire author will then enter the castle with her 70 young guests and their minders for the extravagant party, which is being thrown by Bloomsbury, the British publisher of the best-selling Potter series.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="40"><scu uid="27" label="J.K. Rowling hosted 70 children at Edinburgh Castle for the launch." weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051015.0135"><line>More than 500 people attended a midnight launch party for the book hosted by the publisher at the ruins of Lisbon's Gothic Carmo convent, which stands in testimony to an earthquake which leveled the city in 1755.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>That's how much of a reader I am.&quot;</line><line>&quot;That's a good thing.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050712.0577"><line>A Canadian supermarket chain scrambled to put the magic of Harry Potter back in the box Tuesday after accidentally selling 14 copies of the much-anticipated book days ahead of its scheduled worldwide launch.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="14,33,51"><scu uid="28" label="A Canadian store sold copies of the book before the launch" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>For Sydney resident Agnes Jang, 16, who came dressed head-to-toe as a student of the Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry, the end of the Potter era will be a cause to mourn.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>Moss is still waiting for a Braille version of Katherine Paterson's &quot;Lyddie,&quot; a 1991 book about a young girl's struggle to survive poverty in 19th-century New England.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>&quot;They grip you.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051015.0137"><line>The fantasy series by J.K. Rowling is quite popular in China.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051004.0497"><line>Agent Christopher Little said the series reached the milestone following the publication of &quot;Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince,&quot; the sixth volume about the schoolboy wizard.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="12,20,36,38"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050717.0460"><line>&quot;The fact that a brilliantly written book for children just sold 6.9 million copies in the first 24 hours in the U.S. is cause for celebration, not just for Scholastic but for book lovers everywhere,&quot; said Lisa Holton, president of Scholastic Children's Book Publishing.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0346"><line>&quot;It was a mistake.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050715.0335"><line>While each of the competition winners will receive an autographed copy of the new book, the Scottish National Library said it would be given the first signed version on Saturday morning.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>&quot;It's raining.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050717.0460"><line>&quot;Once again Harry Potter made history.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="18"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>In Hong Kong, a teenage boy leaned against a wall outside a bookstore and began reading a copy immediately after buying it.</line><line>But the party must eventually come to an end.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051001.0176"><line>Fans in costume crammed into bookseller Tropismes which saw &quot;many more than for the last book, and more children because it was a Friday&quot;, according to store manager Brigitte De Meeus.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>At 1,100 pages, the Braille edition is nearly twice as long as the hardcover version.</line><line>A blind kid deserves the same books as a sighted child.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="21"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051015.0135"><line>Rowling worked as an English teacher in Portugal in the 1990s, when she is said to have begun imagining the characters of the Harry Potter books.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051015.0137"><line>According to the Guangming book-lovers' website, the publisher launched the Chinese edition of the fifth Harry Potter book in September 2003, also just three months after the original came out in June that year.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="20"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>Booksellers around the world have profited enormously from the Potter phenomenon, which seems to grow with each new edition.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051015.0135"><line>It is a record first print run for a Portuguese-language version of the series, whose five first books have until now sold some 1.39 million copies in Portugal, a nation of just over 10 million people.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="33"><scu uid="41" label="French, Portuguese and Chinese translations came out in October" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>&quot;The story's really gripping, and I like the fact that the characters are falling in love and getting more mature,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051015.0137"><line>Three months after one of the world's best-sellers, the latest Harry Potter tale was released, its Chinese edition hit local book stores on Saturday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="0,25,48,8"><scu uid="41" label="French, Portuguese and Chinese translations came out in October" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051001.0176"><line>Its central Paris Champs-Elysees branch transformed itself into a &quot;forbidden forest&quot; full of scary creatures, normally off limits to students of magic at Harry's &quot;Hogwart's school&quot; (or the &quot;college de Poudlard&quot; as it is known to French readers).</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050715.0335"><line>A special television show -- &quot;Harry Potter at the Castle: Magic at Midnight&quot; -- on the independent British channel ITV1 will follow the events live, with images also broadcast on a giant screen outside the castle.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051001.0176"><line>&quot;We have sold 120 copies in one-and-a-half hours.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050712.0577"><line>The judge also compelled the unidentified customers to hand over the novel to Raincoast, which has agreed to return them signed by Rowling, along with other gifts, after the official launch.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0346"><line>&quot;We're going to do the right thing,&quot; Mike Muldoon said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050712.0577"><line>Nobody in Canada has spoiled the secret,&quot; said Raincoast's Jamie Broadhurst.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>Only 500 to 600 new Braille titles are published each year _ only about 1 percent of all books published, according to Kim Charlson, the Perkins School's library director.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051001.0176"><line>The first five books in the series, created in 1996, have sold 300 million copies worldwide and more than 17 million copies in French translation, while 100,000 French and 30,000 Swiss fans have already bought the English edition, which has been out since July.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="19"><scu uid="39" label="More than 300 million copies of the Harry Potter books have been sold" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050712.0577"><line>The grocer begged customers to return the books, but if they refused, Canadian publisher Raincoast Book Distribution Ltd. sought an unprecedented injunction from a provincial court to keep the storyline a secret.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="21"><scu uid="32" label="A court injunction was issued to prevent the accidental Canadian purchasers from reading the book prior to the launch" weight="3"/><scu uid="33" label="The Canadian store that sold copies of the book before the launch begged for their return" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050713.0036"><line>&quot;It's so important for blind children to have access to the same cultural phenomena at the same time as their peers,&quot; Holton said.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051015.0137"><line>According to the book's authorized publisher, People's Literature Publishing House, all the 800,000 copies of the first printing of Potter VI were distributed to hundreds of Xinhua Bookstore outlets across the country's major cities.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051015.0135"><line>Booksellers across Portugal saw legions of Harry Potter fans flock to their shelves this weekend as the sixth book in the children's series first dreamt up when its British author lived in the country went on sale in translation at midnight on Friday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="6" sums="10,11,23,25,41,43"><scu uid="41" label="French, Portuguese and Chinese translations came out in October" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050712.0577"><line>As you can imagine, the situation is somewhat fluid,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>The launch was coordinated to occur simultaneously in bookstores across the globe.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051001.0176"><line>A thousand customers visited the Brussels store of major book and music retailer FNAC between 11:00 pm and 1:30 am (2100 to 2330 GMT) and bought over 500 books in a bewitching atmosphere of special effects and smoke.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050712.0577"><line>&quot;The situation right now is contained.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="47"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051001.0176"><line>Hundreds of bookshops in France, Belgium and Switzerland stayed open past the witching hour to welcome hoards of Harry's young admirers, eager to purchase their copy of &quot;Harry Potter et le Prince de Sang-Mele&quot; (&quot;Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince&quot;).<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="22,35,38,40"><scu uid="41" label="French, Portuguese and Chinese translations came out in October" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050716.0100"><line>&quot;Harry Potter has done wonders for children's literacy and for introducing children to the joys of reading, which is great for children and great for the book industry.&quot;</line></document></collection>